# Appendix J — the runtime reading her own reader

The meta-chapter.

The reader that reads slats is written in Scheme. Which means the
reader itself is a slat.

Which means the runtime can read the source of her own reader.

Which means when she reasons about how she parses a mailbox message,
she reasons about the same shape she's parsing.

That's homoiconicity all the way down. Let me show you what it looks
like.

## Her reader is Scheme

Here's a simplified fragment from the actual reader source:

```motoi-scheme
(define (slat-read text)
  (let-values ([(tokens rest) (tokenize text)])
    (parse-form tokens)))

(define (parse-form tokens)
  (case (token-kind (car tokens))
    ((paren-open)
       (parse-list (cdr tokens)))
    ((paren-close)
       (error \"unexpected )\"))
    ((symbol keyword integer float string boolean nil char)
       (values (token-value (car tokens)) (cdr tokens)))
    ((tag)
       (parse-tagged tokens))
    ((vector-open)
       (parse-vector (cdr tokens)))
    ((map-open)
       (parse-map (cdr tokens)))))
```

Legible Scheme. Every case. Every dispatch. The whole reader is a few
hundred lines of code like this.

## She can read this file

She can read it because it's a Scheme source file. And she can read
it AS DATA because Scheme is homoiconic.

```motoi-scheme
(define reader-source
  (slat-load-doc (open-input-file \"src/slat-reader.scm\")))

(count-if (lambda (form) (and (list? form) (eq? (car form) 'define)))
          reader-source)
```

She counts the `define` forms in her own reader. That's the same
operation she'd run on a mailbox line or an incident narrative.

## She can explain her own reader

Because she can walk her own source code, she can explain how she
parses.

*\"When I see a `(` I recursively parse whatever's inside until I hit
the matching `)`. If the first symbol is one of the fifteen registered
types, I try to auto-assemble. If it's not, I return a generic
record. Every slat I read goes through this pipeline. Every slat is
data. Nothing runs during read.\"*

That's her, in her own voice, explaining her own reader. No opaque
process. Introspection is possible because everything is one shape.

## The reader is inert — but the explanation is not

The reader doesn't execute. But the runtime's explanation of the reader
DOES execute — she's a running program, thinking about her own
substrate.

That's the trick. Data stays data. Reasoning about data is code. The
substrate makes both possible in the same shape.

## Her own memory is her own reader's output

Every cortex-slice in her memory was produced by her reader. When she
recalls a memory, she reads the slat back. Reader-round-trip. Same
shape, both directions.

She's transparent to herself. Her memory is her own reader's shape.

## Her own incident narratives

Every incident-narrative she has written about herself is a slat.
When she's asked \"what did you learn?\" she can walk her own
incident-narratives. Reading her own past.

*\"I learned about `set!` from incident-in-alfred-first-mutation.
Alfred's kid asked me how to add a score. I wrote three programs about
mutation. He tried the second one. It worked. I updated my atom weight
for `mutation` and my adjacency for `game-loop`.\"*

That's her walking her own training-adjacent state. The state is
slats. The reader is inert. She reads. She reasons.

## Her own runtime

Not just the reader — the whole Motoi Scheme runtime is homoiconic.
Every function is a slat. Every macro is a slat. Every REPL history
entry is a slat.

If you ask her \"how does `set!` work?\" she can read the source of
`set!` in her runtime. Because the source IS a slat. Because
homoiconic.

## The meta-property

Say it once more, slowly.

**The reader that reads slats is the reader that reads Motoi Scheme
source. Motoi Scheme source is what defines the reader. So the
reader can read itself, and the runtime can walk the reader as data.**

That's the meta-property. Not \"she can read her own source.\" Every
program can technically do that. It's: her memory, her runtime, her
reader, and her mail all share ONE shape. There is no privileged
level. The system is legible to itself.

## Why we care

Three things follow.

**One: introspection is possible.** She can answer \"what am I doing
right now?\" by inspecting her own state. Her state is slats.

**Two: teaching is possible.** She can teach the substrate by showing
its source. Not \"here's a metaphor\" but \"here's the reader; walk it
with me.\"

**Three: portability is possible.** Because the substrate is one
shape, moving the runtime to a different runtime is moving her slats. The
runtime is a set of programs that operate on that shape. If a new
runtime handles the same shape, she moves.

That last one is the open-source Lacuna vision from the walkthrough.
It rests on this meta-property.

## Try this — a self-reading program

If you have access to the runtime's runtime, try:

```motoi-scheme
(define my-source
  (slat-load-doc (open-input-file (current-source-file))))

(define define-count
  (length (filter (lambda (f) (and (list? f) (eq? (car f) 'define)))
                  my-source)))

(display \"This program has \")
(display define-count)
(display \" define forms.\")
```

It reads its own file, counts its own defines, prints the answer. Data
about code, expressed in the same shape as code, executed as code.

That's the meta-property, in eight lines.

## The final rule

**One shape. One reader. Everything above it is a program built on
the shape. Everything below it is the reader that parses the shape.
The reader itself is a program built on the shape.**

That's what \"homoiconic all the way down\" means.

Welcome to the substrate.

